04589nam a22006375i 9780226364810DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016022230  a9780226364810  a(DE-B1597)550097  a(OCoLC)968723399  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aH61.8b.S84 2017 4aH61.8b.S84 2017eb 7aLAN0000002bisacsh04a808.06/63223  aMR 20002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123487:1 aStein, Arlene, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGoing Public :bA Guide for Social Scientists /cArlene Stein, Jessie Daniels. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b9 line drawings, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Guides to Writing, Editing, and Publishing00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. So you want to go public? -- t1. Writing beyond the academy -- t2. Telling stories about your research -- t3. Books for general audiences -- t4. The digital turn -- t5 .Building an audience -- t6. The perils of going public -- t7. Making it count, making a difference -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt a time when policy discussions are dominated by “I feel” instead of “I know,” it is more important than ever for social scientists to make themselves heard. When those who possess in-depth training and expertise are excluded from public debates about pressing social issues—such as climate change, the prison system, or healthcare—vested interests can sway public opinion in uninformed ways. Yet few graduate students, researchers, or faculty know how to do this kind of work—or feel empowered to do it. While there has been an increasing call for social scientists to engage more broadly with the public, concrete advice for starting the conversation has been in short supply. Arlene Stein and Jessie Daniels seek to change this with Going Public, the first guide that truly explains how to be a public scholar. They offer guidance on writing beyond the academy, including how to get started with op-eds and articles and later how to write books that appeal to general audiences. They then turn to the digital realm with strategies for successfully building an online presence, cultivating an audience, and navigating the unique challenges of digital world. They also address some of the challenges facing those who go public, including the pervasive view that anything less than scholarly writing isn’t serious and the stigma that one’s work might be dubbed “journalistic.” Going Public shows that by connecting with experts, policymakers, journalists, and laypeople, social scientists can actually make their own work stronger. And by learning to effectively add their voices to the conversation, researchers can help make sure that their knowledge is truly heard above the digital din.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAcademic writing. 0aCommunication in the social sciences. 0aSocial sciencesxAuthorship. 0aSociologyxAuthorship. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  adigital scholarship.  apublic engagement.  apublic scholarship.  apublic sociology.  awriting op-eds.1 aDaniels, Jessie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFields, Corey.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226364810423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226364810/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles